│ "### 1. Understanding the Issue\n\nThe core of the problem lies in how GVN (Global Value   │
│ Numbering) interacts with the `llvm.assume` intrinsic and the                              │
│ `llvm.lifetime.start`/`llvm.lifetime.end` intrinsics.\n\nThe provided IR contains the      │
│ following sequence:\n1.  `%alloca = alloca i32, align 4, addrspace(1)`: An alloca          │
│ instruction, which by definition, returns a non-null pointer.\n2.  `%cmp = icmp eq ptr     │
│ addrspace(1) %alloca, null`: A comparison checking if the alloca's result is null.\n3.     │
│ `call void @llvm.assume(i1 %cmp)`: An intrinsic that tells the optimizer to assume the     │
│ condition (`%cmp`) is true. This effectively informs the optimizer that `%alloca` is equal │
│ to `null`.\n\nThe optimizer, specifically GVN, correctly deduces from the `llvm.assume`    │
│ that any use of `%alloca` can be replaced by `null`. It then proceeds to do so for all     │
│ subsequent uses, including the calls to `llvm.lifetime.start` and                          │
│ `llvm.lifetime.end`.\n\nThe problem is that `llvm.lifetime.start` and `llvm.lifetime.end`  │
│ have a strict requirement: their pointer argument must be a value derived from an `alloca` │
│ instruction or be `poison`. A `null` constant is not a valid argument. When GVN replaces   │
│ `%alloca` with `null` in these calls, it produces invalid IR. The subsequent Verifier pass │
│ detects this invalid IR and aborts compilation, which is the crash you are                 │
│ observing.\n\n### 2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log\n\nThe `opt` log confirms this diagnosis. The   │
│ crash happens inside the Verifier (`llvm::VerifierPass::run`), and the error message is    │
│ explicit:\n```\nllvm.lifetime.start/end can only be used on alloca or poison\n  call void  │
│ @llvm.lifetime.start.p1(i64 4, ptr addrspace(1) null)\n```\nThis shows that at the time of │
│ verification, the argument to the lifetime intrinsics has already been transformed to      │
│ `null`. The transformation itself is not logged, but the result is what causes the         │
│ verifier to fail. The crash happens *after* GVN has run and modified the IR.\n\n### 3.     │
│ Root Cause Analysis\n\nThe root cause is a missing check within GVN's value replacement    │
│ logic. GVN's `processAssume` function correctly identifies the value equivalence           │
│ (`%alloca` == `null`) and adds it to its internal data structures. Later, during the       │
│ instruction processing phase, GVN replaces operands with their value-numbered              │
│ equivalents.\n\nThe logic for replacing operands does not have a special case to handle    │
│ intrinsics like `llvm.lifetime.start` and `llvm.lifetime.end`, which have specific         │
│ constraints on their operands that go beyond simple type-correctness. GVN should be aware  │
│ that it cannot replace the pointer operand of these intrinsics with a constant like        │
│ `null`, even if it has been told to assume they are equivalent.\n\nThe fix is to make GVN  │
│ aware of these \"special\" intrinsics and prevent it from performing such invalid          │
│ transformations on their arguments.\n\n### 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)\n\nThe fix should be  │
│ applied in `llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/GVN.cpp`, within the `GVN::processInstruction`      │
│ function. This is where GVN iterates over instructions and considers replacing their       │
│ operands. We need to add a check to prevent the replacement for the pointer operand of     │
│ `llvm.lifetime.start` and `llvm.lifetime.end`.\n\n```cpp\n//                               │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/GVN.cpp\n\n// ... inside GVN::processInstruction ...\n      //  │
│ If the operand is a constant, we don't need to do anything.\n      if                      │
│ (isa<Constant>(*Oper))\n        continue;\n\n      // If the operand is an argument, we    │
│ can't force it to be anything.\n      if (isa<Argument>(*Oper))\n        continue;\n\n     │
│ // If the operand is an inline asm, we can't force it to be anything.\n      if            │
│ (isa<InlineAsm>(*Oper))\n        continue;\n\n      // Do not change the pointer operand   │
│ of a lifetime intrinsic.\n      if (auto *II = dyn_cast<IntrinsicInst>(I))\n        if     │
│ (II->isLifetimeStartOrEnd() && Oper == II->getArgOperand(1))\n          continue;\n\n      │
│ // Otherwise, see if we have a value number for this operand.\n      uint32_t OperVN =     │
│ lookupOrAdd(*Oper);\n// ...\n```\n\n### 5. Conclusion\n\nBy adding a check in              │
│ `GVN::processInstruction` to skip operand replacement for the pointer argument of          │
│ `llvm.lifetime.start` and `llvm.lifetime.end` intrinsics, we prevent GVN from creating     │
│ invalid IR. This resolves the Verifier crash while still allowing GVN to perform its other │
│ optimizations correctly. The underlying assumption (`%alloca` is `null`) is contradictory  │
│ and indicates undefined behavior in the source program, but the compiler should not crash  │
│ because of it."})                                                                          │
